<recipe>
    <name>Shikhampuri Kabab</name>
    <indexCharacter>S</indexCharacter>
    <notes></notes>
    <servings>0</servings>
    <instructions>1. Wash mutton mince and squeeze between the palm of your hands to remove excess water.  Wash and soak chana dal in one cup of water for an hour.  Drain and keep aside. 

2. Dry roast red chillies, cinnamon, cloves, peppercorns, cumin seeds, coriander seeds and grind to a fine powder. 

3. Remove stems, wash and finely chop green cillies. Peel, was and finely chop ginger and garlic. 

4. In a large pan, combine mutton mince, chana dal, chopped green chillies, choped ginger and garlic and salt to taste.  Add two cups of water and bring to a boil.  Reduce heat and add the powdered masala and allow to simmer on low heat until almost done and the mixture is dry.  Remove from heat and allow to cool.  When cool, grind the mixture to a paste. 

5. Add garam masala powder and lemon juice to the ground paste and mix well.  Add sesame seeds to the mutton mixture and mix well.  Divide into sixteen portions. 

6. For stuffing, hang yogurt in a muslin cloth for an hour in the refrigerator until most of the moisture has drained away.  Peel, wash and chop onion. Remove stem, was and chop green chilli.  Clean, wash and chop mint leaves.  Add green chilli, onion, mint leaves, salt and roasted cumin seeds to the yogurt. Mix well and divide into sixteen portions. 

7. Take a portion of the mince mixture and roll it into a ball between your palms. Flatten slightly and make an indentation in the center of the meat, like a small cup.  Fill this indentation with a small spoonful of the yogurt stuffing and fold the mixture over to seal.  Similarly shape the rest of the kababs. 

8. Beat eggs and keep in a bowl.  Heat a little oil in the pan. Dip each kabab into the beaten egg and shallow fry the kababs until they are golden brown. 

9. Drain on paper towels and serve hot with onion rings and mint chutney.</instructions>
